[~sjones],

All the images were installed via euca-install-image command.  

The broken images are as follows:
{code}
IMAGE	emi-17204b33	ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-20151214-v2/trusty-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw.manifest.xml	000566698318	available	public	x86_64	machine				instance-store	hvm
IMAGE	emi-2dd9d517	ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-20151209/trusty-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw.manifest.xml	000566698318	available	public	x86_64	machine				instance-store	hvm
IMAGE	emi-795fb78e	ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-20151214/trusty-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw.manifest.xml	000566698318	available	public	x86_64	machine				instance-store	hvm
IMAGE	emi-ef2de937	ubuntu-xenial-x86_64-hvm-20151209/xenial-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw.manifest.xml	000566698318	available	public	x86_64	machine				instance-store	hvm
{code}
They were installed as follows:
{code}
# euca-install-image -i trusty-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw -b ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-20151209 --arch x86_64 --virtualization-type hvm --name ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm --region euca-admin@us-east-1
# euca-install-image -i xenial-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw -b ubuntu-xenial-x86_64-hvm-20151209 --arch x86_64 --virtualization-type hvm --name ubuntu-xenial-x86_64-hvm --region euca-admin@us-east-1
# euca-install-image -i trusty-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw -b ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-20151214 --arch x86_64 --virtualization-type hvm --name ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-v2 --region euca-admin@us-east-1
# euca-install-image -i trusty-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw -b ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-20151214-v2 --arch x86_64 --virtualization-type hvm --name ubuntu-trusty-x86_64-hvm-v3 --bootstrap-url https://bootstrap.c-05.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com/ --region euca-admin@us-east-1
{code}
The working EMI is the following:
{code}
IMAGE	emi-1768c912	ubuntu-xenial-x86_64-hvm-20151217/xenial-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw.manifest.xml	001520216600	available	public	x86_64	machine				instance-store	hvm
{code}
This EMI was installed as follows:
{code}
# euca-install-image -i xenial-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.raw -b ubuntu-xenial-x86_64-hvm-20151217 --arch x86_64 --virtualization-type hvm --name ubuntu-xenial-x86_64-hvm-v2 --region devops-admin@us-east-1 --ec2cert us-east-1-cert.pem
{code}
Hope this helps.

{quote}
I'm not sure when the bootstrap URL is used as I'm not clear exactly what it means for the ec2 certificate to be "available locally"
{quote}
Bootstrap URL was used with both 'eucalyptus/admin' user and 'devops/admin' user.  The cloud certificate locally was a test i did to help narrow down what was going wrong. "Available locally" - i mean shoudln't it not be needed on the client for bundling to work (if bootstrap URL is accessible).

{quote}
I'm also not clear if you are now running the euca-install-image command on the same host for the different users.
{quote}
I didn't run euca-install-image on the same host due to the fact that 'devops/admin' user is part of a federated account created on the 'shared-setup-1' region (this region is being used for account management).  I used the 'eucalyptus/admin' on the CLC of the 'us-east-1' region because its a Eucalyptus system account.

What I mean is that the tool may not be using the bootstrap URL if the certificate is locally available. For example if the configuration for euca2ools contains:

{code}
certificate = /var/lib/eucalyptus/keys/cloud-cert.pem
{code}

[~hspencer], as you are using an aws region name the default configuration for that region is being picked up from /etc/euca2ools/conf.d/aws.ini. You can edit that configuration to remove the "certificate" entry or you can override it in the users us-east-1 euca2ools configuration:

{code}
certificate = /usr/share/euca2ools/certs/cert-ec2.pem
{code}
